did.unittitle: Mick Moloney Irish-American Music and Popular Culture Collection, Part V: Videotapes
did.abstract: Part V of the Mick Moloney Irish-American Music and Popular Culture Collection consists of videotapes acquired in the course of Dr. Moloney's career as folklorist, producer, musician and academic. The tapes include amateur and professional recordings of Moloney's performances; extensive documentation of the 1987 International Village Fair; commercial videotapes collected as teaching aids; and videotapes used as masters and safeties for recording sessions. The tapes are in three formats: VHS cassette, Beta and U-Matic. NOTE: This collection is stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.
did.physloc: 12/23/11 Part V is located in Aisle 59, Range B at Cooper.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material at the Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives
relatedmaterial.p: The Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection is composed of five parts. Taken together, they illustrate Dr. Moloney's career long engagement with Irish-American culture across a wide variety of media with a particular focus on Irish and Irish-American music.

bioghist.head: Historical/Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Mick Moloney Irish-American Music and Popular Culture Collection in the Archives of Irish America at the Tamiment Library, New York University constitutes an aurally and visually rich resource for scholars and students of the Irish-American experience. Videotapes made or collected by Mick Moloney make up Part V of this collection. The tapes were made and/or collected in his capacity as a producer of albums of Irish traditional music; as a folklorist and academic; and as artistic director for International House Philadelphia and for the musical ensemble, The Green Fields of America.

Dr. Mick Moloney (b. 1944 Limerick, Ireland) is Global Distinguished Professor of Music and Irish Studies at New York University (NYU). He immigrated to the United States in 1973 and was based in Philadelphia until moving to New York City in 2006. A musician and folklorist, he has recorded and produced over forty albums of traditional music and acted as advisor for scores of festivals and concerts, as well as being artistic director for the musical ensemble The Green Fields of America. In 1999 Mick Moloney was awarded the National Heritage Award from the National Endowment for the Arts, the highest official honor a traditional artist can receive in the United States. He is the author of the book and CD Far from the Shamrock Shore (2002), as well as numerous essays on Irish music and musical culture, co-editor of Close to the Floor: Irish Dance from the Boreen to Broadway (2009) and has a Ph.D. in folklore and folklife from the University of Pennsylvania.
Nov 15, 1944 - Born, "Glanleam," Castletroy, Limerick
1968 -1971 Member of The Johnstons
1973 - Matriculates at U Penn as a Doctoral Candidate in Folklore
1975 - Co-founds the Philadelphia Ceili Group Festival
1976 - Curates Irish music component of the Smithsonian Folklife Festival

1976 - Receives NEA grant to record Irish music in NY, Boston, Chicago, Philadelphia and Cleveland
1977 - Founds Folklife Center at International House
1978 - Founds Green Fields of America, first federally funded touring group of traditional musicians
1978/1979 - Maintains private booking agency
1978 - Produces Across the Western Ocean radio series with NEA funds
1980 - Fieldwork for the American Folklife Center at the Library of Congress culminating in the curation of the Folklife component of the 1982 World's Fair
1981 - Freelance writer for Radio Telefis Eireann (RTE)
1981 - Writes and produces the film, Did Your Mother Come From Ireland?
1982 - Begins 12-year association with Villanova University as Adjunct Professor in the English Department and Honors Program
1982 - Founds Irish Week at the Augusta Heritage Center, Elkins College, WV
1983 - Tours Africa with the federally funded Festival of Traditional American Dance
1985 - Tours Central America with the federally funded Festival of Mountain Music and Dance
1987 - Directs the International Village Fair for International House, Philadelphia, PA
1990 - Produces the Concert for Joe Doherty, Symphony Space, New York, NY
1992 - Receives Doctorate in Folklore from the University of Pennsylvania
1992 - Begins Folklife Tours of Ireland and Scotland
1996 - Produces the Concert for Peace, Symphony Space, New York, NY
1999 - Receives National Heritage Fellowship Award from the National Endowment of the Arts.
1999 - Joins NYU as Adjunct Professor
2006 - Appointed Global Distinguished Professor of Music and Irish Studies at NYU

custodhist.head: Provenance
custodhist.p: New York University’s Division of Libraries, in conjunction with Glucksman Ireland House at New York University, purchased the Mick Moloney Collection of Irish-American Music and Popular Culture for the Archives of Irish America in 2006. Until transfer to Bobst Library under the supervision of its Head of Collections, Dr. Michael Nash, the materials in this collection were stored in Dr. Moloney’s house in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The Mick Moloney Irish American Music and Popular Culture Collection is composed of five parts. Taken together, they illustrate Dr. Moloney's career long engagement with two centuries of Irish-American musical culture (1806 to 2011, bulk dates 1975-2000) across a wide variety of media and from at least three perspectives: academic, professional and performative.

Mick Moloney's videotape collection composes Part V of this collection. The tapes were made and/or collected in his capacity as a producer of albums of Irish traditional music; as a folklorist and academic; and as artistic director for International House Philadelphia and for the musical ensemble, The Green Fields of America. Part V provides resources for scholars whose focus is the Irish-American experience. Broad themes of immigration and assimilation can be viewed through the lens of Irish-America's engagement with and expression of its own popular culture, primarily its music.

The era most well documented in the Moloney collection (1975-2000) witnessed both a reinvestment by Irish-America in its cultural traditions, and a transition of its musical traditions from home to the stage accompanied by unprecedented national recognition. In this regard, Part V may be of interest to those interested in tracing shifts in federal policies regarding arts funding and programming as well as those interested in the valorization of ethnicity in the U.S. from the 1970s on. In addition, one of Moloney's interests during this period was the rise in prominence of female performers of traditional music, of potential interest to those whose focus is gender. Part V is also very suited to those scholars and performers interested in the repertoire and performance practices of traditional musicians across a variety of ethnicities during the 1980s and 1990s.

Series I: Videotapes, 1982-2000 consists of videotapes pertaining primarily to Moloney's professional life as a performer, promoter, producer and fieldworker, supplemented by some items of personal interest.

A large percentage of the tapes document Moloney's live performances, many at Irish and Folk festivals held in Washington, D.C. (Glen Echo), Dallas, Philadelphia and at the Augusta Heritage Center's Irish Week at Elkins College, W. Va. Moloney's touring ensemble, the Green Fields of America, and his collaboration with Robbie O'Connell and Jimmy Keane are particularly well represented.

Equally significant are the large group of tapes dedicated the International Village Fair, sponsored by Philadelphia's International House in 1987. Moloney devoted a full year organizing this festival and Part V contains at least twenty-nine tapes detailing all aspects of the event and complimenting the extensive paper and photographic documentation found in Part III of the Moloney collection.
In addition to video content, some of the tapes contain audio masters and safety copies of important recording sessions, both for Moloney and for the traditional ensemble, Cherish the Ladies.

Other items of note in Part V are broadcasts; tapes related to Moloney's package tours of Ireland, including those sponsored by the Smithsonian Institution; and a recording of the ceremony at which Moloney received the National Heritage Fellowship Award in 1999.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: These tapes have not been viewed by the archivist in order to double check content. Tape titles were taken verbatim from the tape box or cassette label. The Beta tapes contain audio from recording sessions, not video.
